# No useEffect

**MANDATORY** when writing or reviewing React components in this repo.

Never call `useEffect` directly. Use derived state, event handlers, data-fetching libraries, or `useMountEffect` instead.

Source: [alvinsng/no-use-effect gist](https://gist.github.com/alvinsng/5dd68c6ece355dbdbd65340ec2927b1d)

## Quick Reference

- React docs: [You Might Not Need an Effect](https://react.dev/learn/you-might-not-need-an-effect)

| Instead of useEffect for... | Use |
|----------------------------|-----|
| Deriving state from other state/props | Inline computation (Rule 1) |
| Fetching data | `useQuery` / data-fetching library (Rule 2) |
| Responding to user actions | Event handlers (Rule 3) |
| One-time external sync on mount | `useMountEffect` (Rule 4) |
| Resetting state when a prop changes | `key` prop on parent (Rule 5) |

## When to Apply

- Writing new React components
- Refactoring existing `useEffect` calls
- Reviewing PRs that introduce `useEffect`
- An agent adds `useEffect` "just in case"

## Workflow

1. Identify what the effect is doing — deriving state, fetching data, responding to an event, syncing with an external system, or resetting state.
2. Apply the matching replacement pattern below.
3. Verify: `pnpm lint` and `pnpm typecheck`.

## Escape Hatch: useMountEffect

For rare one-time external sync on mount:

```typescript
export function useMountEffect(effect: () => void | (() => void)) {
  /* eslint-disable no-restricted-syntax */
  useEffect(effect, []);
}
```

## Rule 1: Derive state, do not sync it

```typescript
// BAD
useEffect(() => {
  setFilteredProducts(products.filter((p) => p.inStock));
}, [products]);

// GOOD
const filteredProducts = products.filter((p) => p.inStock);
```

**Smell test:** You are about to write `useEffect(() => setX(deriveFromY(y)), [y])`, or state only mirrors other state/props.

## Rule 2: Use data-fetching libraries

```typescript
// BAD
useEffect(() => {
  fetchProduct(productId).then(setProduct);
}, [productId]);

// GOOD
const { data: product } = useQuery(['product', productId], () => fetchProduct(productId));
```

**Smell test:** Effect does `fetch(...)` then `setState(...)`, or re-implements caching, retries, or cancellation.

## Rule 3: Event handlers, not effects

```typescript
// BAD: flag -> effect -> action
useEffect(() => {
  if (liked) {
    postLike();
    setLiked(false);
  }
}, [liked]);

// GOOD
<button onClick={() => postLike()}>Like</button>
```

**Smell test:** State is a flag so an effect can run the real action.

## Rule 4: useMountEffect for one-time external sync

DOM focus, scroll, third-party widgets, browser API subscriptions.

```typescript
// BAD: guard inside effect
useEffect(() => {
  if (!isLoading) playVideo();
}, [isLoading]);

// GOOD: mount only when ready
if (isLoading) return <LoadingScreen />;
useMountEffect(() => playVideo());
```

For stable singleton/ref/context dependencies, prefer `useMountEffect` over `useEffect([stableRef])`.

## Rule 5: Reset with key, not dependency choreography

```typescript
// GOOD
<VideoPlayer key={videoId} videoId={videoId} />
```

**Smell test:** Effect only resets local state when an ID/prop changes.

## Component Structure Convention

```typescript
export function FeatureComponent({ featureId }: ComponentProps) {
  const { data, isLoading } = useQueryFeature(featureId);
  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);
  const displayName = user?.name ?? "Unknown";
  const handleClick = () => setIsOpen(true);
  if (isLoading) return <Loading />;
  return <div>...</div>;
}
```

Computed values come after hooks and local state — never via `useEffect` + `setState`.
